23
00:01:26,243 --> 00:01:29,146
So like a quick overview, they started out as

24
00:01:29,386 --> 00:01:31,788
these point and click flash games in the early double aughts.

25
00:01:32,288 --> 00:01:35,111
Someone pretty quickly had the idea to translate those

26
00:01:35,151 --> 00:01:36,492
into actual physical spaces.

27
00:01:37,092 --> 00:01:39,214
But the earliest you're seeing those is around that time.

28
00:01:39,294 --> 00:01:41,776
So this is actually still a pretty new genre,

29
00:01:41,956 --> 00:01:45,179
even though it draws from things that have existed

30
00:01:45,259 --> 00:01:46,160
for hundreds of years.

31
00:01:48,699 --> 00:01:53,963
When I'm talking about escape rooms, I'm referring to the specific physical space, people buy

32
00:01:54,003 --> 00:01:58,667
tickets to visit it, they may or may not be locked in, it's usually against fire code

33
00:01:58,707 --> 00:02:01,109
these days to actually lock the door, so that's fine.

34
00:02:02,150 --> 00:02:06,193
There's generally an hour to play the puzzle, sometimes it can be as little as 45 minutes,

35
00:02:06,233 --> 00:02:07,534
