00:26:08,859 --> 00:26:12,002
Yes, I wouldn't be standing here if it wasn't for Myst.

487
00:26:12,622 --> 00:26:15,825
I used to peel off on the side of that little island and just hang out with the dappled

488
00:26:15,865 --> 00:26:19,528
sun coming in, and finally the game would just say, are you going to do anything?

489
00:26:20,517 --> 00:26:25,458
Yeah. So I would actually say like the sort of opposite coin of the work that I make is

490
00:26:26,318 --> 00:26:32,499
untimed, like experience-based stuff. The Now Play, this thing that I highlighted at the beginning,

491
00:26:32,699 --> 00:26:39,080
is situated in a desk and it's supposed to be the experience of reading other people's letters.

492
00:26:39,820 --> 00:26:44,782
And I consider that a game. And it's something that you participate in, you feel everything,

493
00:26:44,802 --> 00:26:48,082
you're looking at it, you're reading between the lines, but you personally decide.

494
00:26:48,600 --> 00:26:52,382
when that experience ends, when you have enough information,

495
00:26:52,482 --> 00:26:53,463
or when you're satisfied.

496
00:26:53,483 --> 00:26:56,385
It's something that her story used really well,

497
00:26:56,565 --> 00:26:57,225
I think, as well.

498
00:26:57,686 --> 00:26:59,126
So there's definitely a place for it.

499
00:26:59,307 --> 00:27:01,888
But yeah, for me, the opposite of the escape rooms

500
00:27:01,948 --> 00:27:04,690
is stuff that's entirely reading, and is untimed,

501
00:27:04,790 --> 00:27:07,152
and is deeply personal and not team-based.

502
00:27:08,512 --> 00:27:10,454
So yeah, there's definitely space for meditation.

503
00:27:10,654 --> 00:27:12,655
Just in your talk, I'm excited to see more of your work.

504
00:27:13,075 --> 00:27:13,356
Thanks.

505
00:27:14,897 --> 00:27:14,957
Hi.

506
00:27:15,377 --> 00:27:20,801
Do you have any insights on how to make people not feel left out in some part of the games?

507
00:27:20,861 --> 00:27:23,102
I always feel like that in escape room games.

508
00:27:23,942 --> 00:27:27,004
Every single player, even on successful teams, says something like that.

509
00:27:27,184 --> 00:27:29,286
They say, oh, I didn't do anything.

510
00:27:29,766 --> 00:27:32,728
And like when you're watching through the cameras, you're like, no, I saw when you picked

511
00:27:32,768 --> 00:27:35,129
up that thing and you made this connection.

512
00:27:35,309 --> 00:27:39,672
The way to do that, I think, is through a sort of debrief afterward, which is something

513
00:27:39,692 --> 00:27:40,893
that LARPs really nail.

514
00:27:41,933 --> 00:27:43,634
It's something where you walk players through

515
00:27:43,715 --> 00:27:45,216
and then you specifically call out,

516
00:27:45,256 --> 00:27:47,037
like you did this and you did this

517
00:27:47,077 --> 00:27:48,157
and you ask somebody, you know,

518
00:27:48,178 --> 00:27:49,779
what did you do that with this thing?

519
00:27:50,739 --> 00:27:52,480
There's also a thing from LARP called froth,

520
00:27:52,701 --> 00:27:54,622
which is a collective myth making that occurs

521
00:27:54,662 --> 00:27:55,242
when you're sort of,

522
00:27:56,463 --> 00:27:57,884
when the players are telling the story,

523
00:27:57,964 --> 00:28:00,206
so they're sort of world building after the fact.

524
00:28:00,706 --> 00:28:02,387
So just making room to encourage that

525
00:28:02,427 --> 00:28:04,148
I think would be really helpful with that feeling,

526
00:28:04,208 --> 00:28:07,350
but everybody feels that way too, so yeah.

527
00:28:08,604 --> 00:28:15,986
Yeah, that ties very much into my question, because I usually have a similar feeling after doing a room escape game,

528
00:28:16,187 --> 00:28:22,369
and I feel like, man, I'd really enjoy doing this with one or maybe two other people, instead of five, six, seven, eight,

529
00:28:22,769 --> 00:28:25,790
and we're all just looking at different corners and shouting at each other, like,

530
00:28:25,830 --> 00:28:31,231
did anyone find that combination yet? And like, oh, you solved that? I didn't even see that part of the puzzle.

531
00:28:31,351 --> 00:28:31,612
Yeah.

532
00:28:37,774 --> 00:28:42,679
puzzles solved by groups where you don't necessarily get to see the whole picture,

533
00:28:42,799 --> 00:28:47,504
like sit down with the letter and put the narrative together in your head quietly in your own time.

534
00:28:48,281 --> 00:28:50,823
So that's kind of where the cinematic moment stuff comes in.

535
00:28:51,123 --> 00:28:54,825
We usually try to have people branching off into different areas and spaces,

536
00:28:54,925 --> 00:28:57,827
but when there's some sort of story thing that we need them to see,

537
00:28:58,187 --> 00:28:59,228
we drive them together.

538
00:28:59,248 --> 00:29:03,370
That's something that you see in theater like Sleep No More, for example.

539
00:29:03,850 --> 00:29:08,433
For the big major scenes, all of the actors all converge physically on the same space

540
00:29:08,493 --> 00:29:09,374
and something plays out.

541
00:29:09,834 --> 00:29:11,595
So you can choose to not participate in that,

542
00:29:11,755 --> 00:29:14,036
but you're also missing a huge part of it.

543
00:29:14,997 --> 00:29:17,900
So, yeah, it's just very tightly structured in that way

544
00:29:17,981 --> 00:29:20,103
to make sure that there is always something

545
00:29:20,123 --> 00:29:20,784
for people to do.

546
00:29:21,164 --> 00:29:23,647
I'd say the sweet spot is generally eight people as well

547
00:29:23,987 --> 00:29:25,409
for an hour long game, so.

548
00:29:25,829 --> 00:29:26,109
Thank you.

549
00:29:27,797 --> 00:29:31,279
You had mentioned wanting escape rooms to be taken as seriously as theater,

550
00:29:31,599 --> 00:29:34,360
and I'm trying to figure out the intersections between theater and gaming.

551
00:29:34,520 --> 00:29:40,543
And one of the things that even something like Sleep No More doesn't have,

552
00:29:40,583 --> 00:29:43,724
that games have, is a fail state, which escape rooms have.

553
00:29:43,744 --> 00:29:45,265
And so I was just wondering your thoughts,

554
00:29:45,565 --> 00:29:47,425
as something that I've been trying to figure out myself, of like,

555
00:29:47,866 --> 00:29:51,387
how do you make a fail state still narratively satisfying?

556
00:29:53,083 --> 00:29:55,184
For our games, we try and get everybody

557
00:29:55,244 --> 00:29:57,005
to at least a particular part in the story,

558
00:29:57,045 --> 00:29:59,126
which I'd say is about at the 80% mark.

559
00:29:59,406 --> 00:30:01,227
So they've seen everything there is to see.

560
00:30:01,247 --> 00:30:04,889
In Spark of Resistance, that's where the turn happens.

561
00:30:05,089 --> 00:30:06,050
Like they've been betrayed,

562
00:30:06,070 --> 00:30:09,392
and they're tasked with setting off an EMP device.

563
00:30:09,792 --> 00:30:11,453
So whether they set that off or not

564
00:30:11,533 --> 00:30:12,754
is sort of beside the point.

565
00:30:12,794 --> 00:30:14,114
They've already absorbed everything.

566
00:30:14,555 --> 00:30:17,536
And it is really a lot of work to get players to that point

567
00:30:17,596 --> 00:30:19,858
if they're sort of not enjoying the rest of the game.

568
00:30:21,078 --> 00:30:23,941
But I would say check out Strange Bird Immersive.

569
00:30:24,001 --> 00:30:25,322
They're based in Houston, Texas,

570
00:30:25,362 --> 00:30:28,625
and they do a seance theater experience

571
00:30:28,645 --> 00:30:30,627
that's sort of built around an escape room.

572
00:30:31,047 --> 00:30:33,749
So it's a literal integration of theater into a game.

573
00:30:34,330 --> 00:30:36,612
So I think whether or not you succeed in that game

574
00:30:36,652 --> 00:30:38,033
sort of doesn't matter to the story

575
00:30:38,073 --> 00:30:39,594
that's on either end of it as well.

576
00:30:39,654 --> 00:30:41,856
So that is a potential structure to look at.

577
00:30:42,096 --> 00:30:42,877
Awesome, thank you so much.

578
00:30:44,290 --> 00:30:46,271
Hi, thank you for coming here.

579
00:30:46,591 --> 00:30:49,774
I'm creating my own mixed reality game in immersive theater.

580
00:30:50,194 --> 00:30:52,175
So I feel your talk is super helpful.

581
00:30:52,796 --> 00:30:55,958
I wonder if you can talk a little bit about the strategies

582
00:30:56,478 --> 00:30:59,740
for how do we balance the player's free will

583
00:31:00,041 --> 00:31:02,742
and the limitation our game rules set.

584
00:31:02,762 --> 00:31:05,885
Because usually if a player wants to do things

585
00:31:07,646 --> 00:31:09,667
the game designer doesn't intend to,

586
00:31:10,027 --> 00:31:13,170
that will ruin or create distractions, that experience.

587
00:31:13,622 --> 00:31:16,523
I mean, that's part of what the playtesting is that we do.

588
00:31:16,543 --> 00:31:22,547
I would say in our rooms, players never do anything that we do not want them to do, even

589
00:31:22,587 --> 00:31:24,428
if they believe that they are secretly.

590
00:31:25,509 --> 00:31:29,591
Because at a certain point, doing what they want to do in a physical room means they're

591
00:31:29,611 --> 00:31:30,132
going to get hurt.

592
00:31:31,673 --> 00:31:34,554
It's probably different for mixed reality, I'm sure.

593
00:31:35,814 --> 00:31:37,935
But I would say, instead of trying to prevent them

594
00:31:37,975 --> 00:31:40,216
to do that, to build space for that to happen,

595
00:31:41,776 --> 00:31:46,398
sort of a side note, I took a trip to play Escape Rooms

596
00:31:46,518 --> 00:31:49,439
for a full week in Malaysia, and the address for that

597
00:31:49,479 --> 00:31:51,020
is up here, it's every game in this city.

598
00:31:51,820 --> 00:31:54,661
And in one of the games, it was set in a classroom,

599
00:31:55,382 --> 00:31:56,922
and we were each given name tags.

600
00:31:57,322 --> 00:31:58,263
for each of the students.

601
00:31:58,443 --> 00:32:02,246
And so, the first group in our cluster that went through it

602
00:32:02,386 --> 00:32:04,267
like role-played as these characters

603
00:32:04,307 --> 00:32:05,348
that they were just making up.

604
00:32:05,848 --> 00:32:07,930
Then they created roles for the next group

605
00:32:08,150 --> 00:32:09,751
to take on with secret roles

606
00:32:09,831 --> 00:32:12,293
that we weren't allowed to communicate to the other players.

607
00:32:12,353 --> 00:32:15,195
So like that emergent behavior that we came up with

608
00:32:15,896 --> 00:32:18,097
made that game something really, really special.

609
00:32:18,618 --> 00:32:20,939
So I think just like creating the opportunity for that

610
00:32:20,959 --> 00:32:22,520
and then not stepping on people

611
00:32:22,560 --> 00:32:24,462
when it's starting to happen as long as they're safe

612
00:32:24,522 --> 00:32:26,783
is probably a good way to approach it.

613
00:32:27,356 --> 00:32:27,716
Thank you.

614
00:32:29,878 --> 00:32:34,142
Hi, so I am a narrative designer.

615
00:32:34,262 --> 00:32:37,525
I'm currently working on a couple of historical ARG projects

616
00:32:38,006 --> 00:32:41,009
that are creating a story and a narrative game

617
00:32:41,089 --> 00:32:42,490
around real world artifacts.

618
00:32:42,930 --> 00:32:44,572
And I'm wondering if you have any advice

619
00:32:44,652 --> 00:32:46,674
for creating this sort of narrative space

620
00:32:47,254 --> 00:32:50,657
when the boundary between what is part of the game

621
00:32:50,697 --> 00:32:53,700
and what isn't is not as clear as a room.

622
00:32:55,083 --> 00:32:56,803
For alternate reality game stuff,

623
00:32:56,883 --> 00:32:58,704
I think probably players are gonna read

624
00:32:58,944 --> 00:33:01,885
10 to 20 times more into it than you've intended,

625
00:33:03,005 --> 00:33:04,726
which is kinda nice as the designer

626
00:33:04,766 --> 00:33:06,146
to not have to do that work.

627
00:33:07,107 --> 00:33:08,647
So I would just say, again,

628
00:33:08,707 --> 00:33:10,448
it comes down to play testing.

629
00:33:10,828 --> 00:33:12,188
You're always gonna be surprised

630
00:33:12,248 --> 00:33:13,529
by what is emerging from that,

631
00:33:13,629 --> 00:33:15,669
but if you practice enough in advance,

632
00:33:15,849 --> 00:33:17,130
and I know that's really difficult

633
00:33:17,270 --> 00:33:19,190
for ARGs and live events in particular.

634
00:33:20,251 --> 00:33:23,875
But the more that you can anticipate, the better it's going to be on the other side.

635
00:33:24,335 --> 00:33:27,899
But also maybe don't worry about it too much because they will come up with all sorts of

636
00:33:27,939 --> 00:33:29,540
like fun facts and connections.

637
00:33:30,521 --> 00:33:34,265
Then I would work those into the game in a way that feels rewarding as if you had been

638
00:33:34,285 --> 00:33:35,466
doing it on purpose the whole time.

639
00:33:35,947 --> 00:33:36,247
Thank you.

640
00:33:36,807 --> 00:33:36,988
Sure.

641
00:33:38,276 --> 00:33:39,657
Hi, thank you for the great talk.

642
00:33:39,877 --> 00:33:40,657
Oh, sorry.

643
00:33:41,418 --> 00:33:44,800
We have to wrap it up, but I'm going to go to the lounge over

644
00:33:44,840 --> 00:33:46,941
there if you two want to follow me over.

645
00:33:46,961 --> 00:33:48,442
We can keep chatting.

646
00:33:49,062 --> 00:33:49,503
Cool, thanks.

